Voronoi polygons in Python¶

Introduction¶

We are revisiting voronoi polygons again. Last time we did them in R. However, our curious, restless mind also wants test them under the fangs of python. But first, what are the uses of Voronoi polygons? Credited to the Ukrainian born academic George Voronyi, they are used to show how a specific location within a polygon is closer to the sample point in that polygon than any other sample point. George may have received the glory for this, but its actual use stems way back to the mid 19th Century, when the all famous Jon Snow used them to identify the source of London's cholera outbreak in 1854. By the way, if you could be having this doctor's number, holla me... I need an appointment with him for asking a question as such!

Below are some of the uses of voronoi polygons.

  1. Voronoi’s are used to construct maps of representiveness, for example points experiencing the same precipitation
  2. Voronoi diagrams are used in the research of socio-economic phenomena. Polygon’s in their classic form were used to determine transportation accessibility of railway stations and other transportation stops
  3. The method was used to analyze spatial patterns of distribution and accessibility of discount stores to determine the accessibility of green areas in certain large cities of Europe
  4. Voronoi diagrams have been used to delimit school zones and availability of medical services in an area called Presov, Slovakia
  5. In research conducted in the Beijing agglomeration, voronoi’s were used to determine the zone of transit transportation
  6. Voronoi polygons were used to delimit maritime zones in the Gulf of Salwa between Saudi Arabia and Qatar

Another name by which voronoi polygons go by is Thiessen polygons, after the American meteorologist Alfred Thiessen. However, since we are not starting an academic war we will just go by their name attributed to the earlier inventor, George Voronoi.

Loading the datasets¶

For this voronoi plotting experiment, we will not tread too far from Jon Snow's initial medical purposes. We shall use voronoi polygons to draw regions indicating the spatial coverage for a sample of Canadian hospitals. Canada is the second largest country worldwide by the way, so plotting voronois of health centres, even just a sample, will be an interesting mix. The Canadian shapefile is available from this link here.

Now, let's first of all load the necessary modules.

Let's introduce some data science. You may have noticed that the data has some missing values, represented by the 'Not A Number' or NaN values as they are commonly known. An example is the row at index 1 where both Lat-Lon values are missing. If a dataset that we want to georeference is missing its Lat-Lon values, of what use is it to a geospatial expert? Just axe it out. Let's remove these rows with missing Lat-Lon values along with those of their own kind. The dropna method will drop them like a hot potato.

Pre-requisite geospatial operations¶

One can plot voronoi polygons even within a multipolygon dataset such as our Canadian counties shapefile used so far. However, because drawing voronois in python is far more complex than in R, we shall use a dissolved shapefile for this. The aggregate shapefile was created by dissolving the boundaries using Qgis Vector > Geoprocessing > Dissolve tool.

Once, you have done the above, convert the dissolved shapefile from its local CRS to the global CRS ('4326'). Different spatial files work together so long as they are in the same CRS, like two well coordinated cogwheels. Thereafter, load the dissolved shapefile into your Jupyter environment. In our case, the dissolved shapefile was named canada_dissolved_4326.shp. As highly generous fellows, we decided to provide this dissolved shapefile for free to save you from this hustle.

# Load the dissolved Canada administrative shapefile with CRS EPSG:4326

Before one draws voronoi polygons, the boundary shapefile --the canadaBoundary should be a union of the polygon. Secondly, the coordinates of the points have to be in a numpy array. Why all these requirements? Ask the makers of the voronoi modules, not us!

In [28]:
# Make union of the polygon from canadaBoundary
boundaryShape = unary_union(canadaBoundary.geometry)
In [29]:
# Convert canadaHospitalsGdf3 into an array of coordinates
coords = points_to_coords(canadaHospitalsGdf3.geometry)
In [30]:
# calculate the Voronoi regions, cut them with the geographic area shape and assign the points to them
region_polys, region_pts = voronoi_regions_from_coords(coords, boundaryShape)

The following is the description of the region_polys and region_pts from the voronoi module creators.

  • **region_polys** - is a dict that maps Voronoi region IDs to shapely Polygon objects that represent the shape of the respective Voronoi region
  • **region_pts** - is a dict that maps the same Voronoi region IDs as in region_polys to a list of indices into coords, i.e. these indices represent the points that belong to this Voronoi region. Usually, this is only a single point. However, in case of duplicate points (i.e. two or more points have exactly the same coordinates) all duplicate points are listed for the respective Voronoi region

To plot the voronoi polygons, we shall use the plotting tools specific for this endeavour. They are subplot_for_map and plot_voronoi_polys_with_points_in_area.

In [ ]:
# Plotting modules for voronoi polygns
from geovoronoi.plotting import subplot_for_map, plot_voronoi_polys_with_points_in_area

Now that we've loaded the requisite voronoi plotting modules, let's put them to work. The following code will now plot the voronoi plots for us.

In [ ]:
# The format for plotting the voronoi polygons
fig, ax = subplot_for_map()
plot_voronoi_polys_with_points_in_area(ax, boundaryShape, region_polys, coords, region_pts)
plt.show()

From the above generated voronoi polygons, it is evident that the lower the number of hospitals, the larger their spatial area coverage.

Conclusion¶

In this exercise, we created voronoi polygons by first loading the Canadian administrative shapefile and the hospital datasets. The hospital dataset was converted into a point geodataframe. Just like most geospatial operations, both the shapefile and the hospital dataset were transformed to a common CRS to enable overlaying. Thereafter, an array of coordinates was extracted from the points hospital geodataframe, which together with boundary of Canada, was used to create a voronoi diagram.
